T1  - A Multilevel Field Investigation of Emotional Labor, Affect, Work Withdrawal, and Gender
AU  - Scott, Brent A.
AU  - Barnes, Christopher M.
Y1  - 2011/02/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.59215086
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2011.59215086
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 116
EP  - 136
VL  - 54
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Using experience-sampling methodology, we examined within-individual relationships among emotional labor, negative and positive affective states, and work withdrawal, as well as the moderating role of gender. Fifty-eight bus drivers completed two daily surveys over a two-week period, producing 415 matched surveys. Results of hierarchical linear models revealed that affective states worsened when employees engaged in surface acting but improved when they engaged in deep acting. Surface acting was positively associated with work withdrawal, and state negative affect mediated this relationship. Results also revealed moderating effects of gender: the within-individual relationships were stronger for females than for males.
AB  - Using experience-sampling methodology, we examined within-individual relationships among emotional labor, negative and positive affective states, and work withdrawal, as well as the moderating role of gender. Fifty-eight bus drivers completed two daily surveys over a two-week period, producing 415 matched surveys. Results of hierarchical linear models revealed that affective states worsened when employees engaged in surface acting but improved when they engaged in deep acting. Surface acting was positively associated with work withdrawal, and state negative affect mediated this relationship. Results also revealed moderating effects of gender: the within-individual relationships were stronger for females than for males.
