T1  - On Becoming Extraordinary: The Content and Structure of the Developmental Networks of Major League Baseball Hall of Famers
AU  - Cotton, Richard D.
AU  - Shen, Yan
AU  - Livne-Tarandach, Reut
Y1  - 2011/02/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.59215081
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2011.59215081
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 15
EP  - 46
VL  - 54
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We explore the structure and content of developmental networks depicted in 62 National Baseball Hall of Fame induction speeches to identify which developers and what support mattered most to inductees' career achievement. Our analysis illustrates two new support subfunctions (?freedom and opportunity for skill development? and ?inspiration and motivation?) and shows that first-ballot inductees had larger, more diverse developmental networks featuring greater multiplexity and more single-function ties, plus greater supplementary psychosocial and complementary career support from a wider range of core and peripheral career communities, than later-ballot inductees. We conclude with a theoretical model of extraordinary career achievement.
AB  - We explore the structure and content of developmental networks depicted in 62 National Baseball Hall of Fame induction speeches to identify which developers and what support mattered most to inductees' career achievement. Our analysis illustrates two new support subfunctions (?freedom and opportunity for skill development? and ?inspiration and motivation?) and shows that first-ballot inductees had larger, more diverse developmental networks featuring greater multiplexity and more single-function ties, plus greater supplementary psychosocial and complementary career support from a wider range of core and peripheral career communities, than later-ballot inductees. We conclude with a theoretical model of extraordinary career achievement.
